A rational function will have a vertical asymptote at a certain $x$-value if the denominator is equal to zero at that $x$-value.

So, we need to find the $x$-value for which the denominator $5x-7$ is equal to zero.

Setting $5x-7=0$, we can solve for $x$:

\begin{align*}
5x-7&=0 \\
5x&=7 \\
x&=\frac{7}{5}
\end{align*}

Therefore, there is a vertical asymptote at $x=\boxed{\frac{7}{5}}$.
